    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>No Substitute for Nutrients</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jack Challem letter on January 23 article about cholesterol says that good nutrition in key to keeping healthy cholesterol balance</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''An Old Cholesterol Remedy Is New Again'' (Jan. 23): Medicine's faith in pharmaceuticals is another example of how people mistakenly believe they can change fundamental processes in nature. The age-old problem with pharmaceutical treatments is that no drug can replace the function of a nutrient, in this instance niacin (vitamin B3).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''An Old Cholesterol Remedy Is New Again'' (Jan. 23): Medicine's faith in pharmaceuticals is another example of how people mistakenly believe they can change fundamental processes in nature. The age-old problem with pharmaceutical treatments is that no drug can replace the function of a nutrient, in this instance niacin (vitamin B3).</p>
        <p>Drugs work -- if one can call it ''work'' -- by interfering with normal biochemical processes. In contrast, nutrients function by providing the normal biochemical substrates for more complex chemicals and reactions. All roads eventually point back to nutrition: our entire biochemistry, including our genes, depends on nutrients, not drugs.</p>
        <p>Jack Challem  Tucson</p>
      </block>
